04413nam a22006255i 9780674271593DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20112011mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806742715937 a10.4159/97806742715932doi  a(DE-B1597)612946  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aJC423b.C6473 2010eb 7aPHI0190002bisacsh04a320.012231 aCohen, Joshua, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Arc of the Moral Universe and Other Essays /cJoshua Cohen. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (426 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIntroduction -- tI. Justice in History -- t1 The Arc of the Moral Universe -- tII. Reflections on the Democratic Tradition -- t2 Structure, Choice, and Legitimacy: Locke’s Theory of the State -- t3 Democratic Equality -- t4 A More Democratic Liberalism -- t5 For a Democratic Society -- t6 Knowledge, Morality, and Hope: The Social Thought of Noam Chomsky -- t7 Reflections on Habermas on Democracy -- t8 A Matter of Demolition? Susan Okin on Justice and Gender -- tIII. Global Justice -- t9 Minimalism about Human Rights: The Most We Can Hope For? -- t10 Is There a Human Right to Democracy? -- t11 Extra Rempublicam Nulla Justitia? -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this collection of essays, Joshua Cohen locates ideas about democracy in three far-ranging contexts. First, he explores the relationship between democratic values and history. He then discusses democracy in connection with the views of defining political theorists in the democratic tradition: John Locke, John Rawls, Noam Chomsky, Juergen Habermas, and Susan Moller Okin. Finally, he examines the place of democratic ideals in a global setting, suggesting an idea of “global public reason”—a terrain of political justification in global politics in which shared reason still plays an essential role. All the essays are linked by his overarching claim that political philosophy is a practical subject intended to orient and guide conduct in the social world. Cohen integrates moral, social-scientific, and historical argument in order to develop this stance, and he further confronts the question of whether a society conceived in liberty and dedicated to equality can endure. At Gettysburg, President Lincoln forcefully stated the question and expressed both hope and concern over this same struggle about an affirmative answer. By enabling us to trace the arc of the moral universe, the essays in this volume—along with the companion collection, Philosophy, Politics, Democracy—give us some reasons for sharing that hope.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDemocracy. 0aPolitical sciencexPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh1 aRogers, Joel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSabel, Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999z978311044221240uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674271593?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674271593423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674271593/original  a978-3-11-044221-2  HUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999c1893d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles